=== RAW MODEL ANSWER ===
Answer: Step 1: Form the aryl-ethyl bromide fragment by Williamson ether synthesis: 4-(2-bromoethyl)phenol + 4-phenyl-1-bromobutane, K2CO3 (acetone/DMF) → 1-(2-bromoethyl)-4-(4-phenylbutoxy)benzene | Step 2: Alkylate diethyl acetamidomalonate with 1-bromopropane under NaOEt/EtOH to give diethyl 2-acetamido-2-propylmalonate | Step 3: Re-deprotonate that malonate (NaOEt) and alkylate with 1-(2-bromoethyl)-4-(4-phenylbutoxy)benzene to obtain diethyl 2-acetamido-2-propyl-2-[2-(4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl)ethyl]malonate | Step 4: Hydrolysis/decarboxylation of the disubstituted malonate (aq HCl, reflux) → 2-amino-2-propyl-4-[4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl]butanoic acid | Step 5: Protect the amine with Boc2O/base to give N-Boc-2-amino-2-propyl-4-[4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl]butanoic acid | Step 6: Convert the acid to the corresponding methyl or ethyl ester (e.g. MeOH/HCl or SOCl2/MeOH) to form the N-Boc amino ester | Step 7: Reduce the ester to the primary alcohol with LiBH4 (Boc-compatible ester reduction) to furnish the target CCC(CO)(CCc1ccc(OCCCCc2ccccc2)cc1)NC(=O)OC(C)(C)C.

